es, Sambre, France and Flanders 1914\u201318, Piave, Vittorio Veneto'''*''', Italy 1917\u201318, Struma, Doiran 1917'''*''', Macedonia 1915\u201318, Suvla, Sari Bair'''*''', Scimitar Hill, Gallipoli 1915\u201316, Egypt 1916, Tigris 1916, Kut al Amara 1917, Baghdad'''*''', Mesopotamia 1916\u201318, Persia 1918<ref name=dan-bh />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;vertical-align: top;\" | Second World War\n| Defence of Escaut'''*''', St Omer-La-Bass\u00e9e, Wormhoudt, Cassel'''*''', Villers Bocage, Mont Pincon'''*''', Falaise'''*''', Risle Crossing, Le Havre, Zetten, North-West Europe 1940 '44\u201345'''*''', Taukyan'''*''', Paungde'''*''', Monywa 1942, North Arakan, Mayu Tunnels, Pinwe'''*''', Shweli, Myitson'''*''', Burma 1942 '44\u201345'''*'''<ref name=dan-bh />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;vertical-align: top;\" | Korean War\n| Hill 327, Imjin'''*''', Korea 1950\u201351'''*'''<ref name=dan-bh />\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | Battle honours and honorary distinctions awarded to affiliated units\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;vertical-align: top;\" | 4th Battalion (Militia)\n| St. Helena 1901, South Africa 1899\u201302<ref name=reg-org-glos />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;vertical-align: top;\" | 1st and 2nd Volunteer Battalions\n| South Africa 1899\u201302<ref name=\"Daniell p. 199\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space: nowrap;vertical-align: top;\" | 5th Battalion (TA)\n| A badge of the Reconnaissance Corps with years '1944\u20131945' and scroll 'North-West Europe'<ref name=dan-bh />\n|-\n|}\n\n==Victoria Crosses==\n[[File:Lieutenant Colonel James Power Carne VC, DSO.jpg|thumb|Lieutenant-Colonel Carne]]\nThe following were awarded the Victoria Cross, Britain's highest award for bravery, while serving with the Gloucestershire Regiment:<ref>Littlewood pp. 184\u2013186 & 188\u2013190</ref><ref>Daniell p. 366</ref>\n* [[Adrian Carton de Wiart]]&nbsp;\u2013 attached to the 8th Battalion from the [[4th Royal Irish Dragoon Guards]]. Awarded for actions during the First World War;\n* [[Manley Angell James]]&nbsp;\u2013 8th Battalion. Awarded for actions during the First World War;\n* [[Francis George Miles]]&nbsp;\u2013 1/5th Battalion. Awarded for actions during the First World War;\n* [[Hardy Falconer Parsons]]&nbsp;\u2013 14th Battalion. Awarded posthumously for actions during the First World War;\n* [[James Power Carne]]&nbsp;\u2013 1st Battalion. Awarded for actions during the Korean War;\n* [[Philip Curtis]]&nbsp;\u2013 attached to the 1st Battalion from the Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry. Awarded posthumously for actions during the Korean War.\n[[Daniel Burges]], a temporary Lieutenant-Colonel in the Gloucestershire Regiment, was awarded the VC during the First World War while commanding the 7th Battalion [[South Wales Borderers]].<ref>Littlewood p. 187</ref>\n\n==Colonels of the Regiment==\nThe following served in the ceremonial position of [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel of the Regiment]]:<ref>Daniell p. 420</ref>\n* 1881 Major-General Julius E. Goodwyn CB (Last colonel of the 28th Regiment of Foot)\n* 1881 Lieutenant-General Sir [[Thomas Montagu Steele|Thomas M. Steel]] KCB (Last colonel of the 61st Regiment of Foot)\n* 1883 General John William Sidney Smith CB\n* 1897 Lieutenant-General Sir John Patrick Redmond CB\n* 1902 Lieutenant-General William Roberts CB\n* 1912 Major-General Sir [[Francis Howard (British Army officer)|Francis Howard]] KCB KCMG\n* 1913 Major-General Alexander L. Emerson\n* 1918 General Sir [[John Cowans|John Steven Cowans]]\n* 1921 Lieutenant-General Right Honourable Sir [[Frederick Shaw (British Army officer)|Frederick Shaw]] KCB\n* 1931 Brigadier-General Alexander W. Pagan DSO\n* 1947 Lieutenant-General Sir [[Harry Edward de Robillard Wetherall|H. Edward de R. Wetherall]] KBE CB DSO MC\n* 1954 Major-General Charles E. A. Firth CB CBE DSO\n* 1964 Brigadier Philip C. S. Heidenstam CBE\n* 1971 Brigadier Anthony P. A. Arengo-Jones OBE\n* 1978 General Sir [[Anthony Farrar-Hockley]] KCB DSO MBE MC M.Litt\n* 1984 Lieutenant-General Sir [[John Waters (British Army officer, born 1935)|John Waters]] KCB CBE\n* 1991\u20131994 Major-General Robin Digby Grist OBE (to RGBW}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|first=Ian Frederick William |last=Beckett|title=Britain's Part-Time Soldiers: The Amateur Military Tradition: 1558\u20131945|publisher= Pen & Sword Military|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire|year= 2011|isbn=978-1-84884-395-0}}\n* {{cite book|first=David Scott |last=Daniell|authorlink=David Scott Daniell|title=Cap of Honour: The 300 Years of the Gloucestershire Regiment|publisher=Sutton Publishing|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|year= 2005|orig-year=First published 1951|edition=3rd|isbn= 978-0-7509-4172-3}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Grazebrook|first=R.M. |title=The Back Badge of the Gloucestershire Regiment|journal=Army Historical Research|volume=24|number=99|publisher=Society for Army Historical Research|year=1946|pages=112\u2013113|jstor=44220713}}\n* {{cite book|first=E. D.|last=Harvey|title=The Imjin Roll|publisher=Forces & Corporate Publishing|location=Rushden, Northamptonshire|year=2011|isbn=978-0-9529597-6-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=F. W.|last=Harvey|title=The Lost Novel of FW Harvey: A War Romance|publisher=The History Press|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|year=2014|isbn=978-0-7509-5971-1}}\n* {{cite web |title=The Fifth Division in the Great War |last1=Hussey |first1=A. H. |last2=Inman |first2=D. S. |authorlink= |year=1921 |publisher=Nisbet |location=London|edition= |url=https://archive.org/details/fifthdivisioning00huss |accessdate=9 October 2016 |isbn=978-1-84342-267-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=James|first=Edward|title=British Regiments, 1914\u201318|year=1978|publisher=Naval & Military Press|location=Uckfield, East Sussex|isbn=978-0-906304-03-7}}\n* {{cite book|first=Christine |last=Jorden